# Developer Notes – Markdown to Calendar

This document describes how the single-file web app works so you can modify or extend it.

The entire app lives in:

- `obsidian-daily-notes-to-ics.html`

🌐 **Live at:** [dilpreetsinghh.github.io/Markdown-to-Calendar](https://dilpreetsinghh.github.io/Markdown-to-Calendar/)

It contains:

- HTML for controls and layout.
- Embedded CSS for basic styling.
- Vanilla JavaScript for:
  - Folder selection via three methods: File System Access API, `webkitdirectory` input, and Drag & Drop.
  - Recursive scanning of `.md` files.
  - Parsing of time-blocked tasks and their descriptions.
  - Optional calendar tagging based on `#tags` or `@labels`.
  - iCalendar (`text/calendar`) generation and file download.

There are no external dependencies.

---

## Core state

Key global variables:

- `collectedFiles: File[]`: all `.md` files collected from the selected folder.
- `parsedEvents: ParsedEvent[]`: all raw events parsed from markdown.
- `tagMode: 'none' | 'hash' | 'at'`: how we interpret tags on a line.
- `tagConfig: Record<string, { enabled: boolean; name: string }>`: configuration for each discovered tag.
- `stripTagsFromSummary: boolean`: whether to remove calendar tags from event titles.
- `needsRescanForTagMode: boolean`: whether the user has changed `tagMode` since the last scan.

Each **event** has the shape:

```ts
interface ParsedEvent {
  summary: string;      // original task line after the time range
  description: string;  // joined indented bullets
  location: string;     // currently unused
  start: Date;
  end: Date;
  fileName: string;     // source .md filename
  tags: string[];       // raw tags/labels found on the line
}
```

After applying tag configuration and export settings, we use an extended shape with:

```ts
interface ExportEvent extends ParsedEvent {
  calendarKey: string | null; // calendar/category name
  summary: string;            // possibly stripped of calendar tags
}
```

